Anonymous Sat 13 Jul 2024 11:26:02 No.67357274 Report
Quoted By: >>67358131
>>67357088
>He adds to his ideas document
>worldbuilding disease
This is such a horrible fucking meme and it keeps cropping up everywhere.
The worst part is that they take PRIDE in their heap of "ideas," as though a farmer is better with a warehouse of sacks of seeds rather than with one producing crop.

Understand that this person is DEPRESSED. It isn't necessarily emo depression, and it doesn't need to be creativity related. It could be loneliness, it could be disappointment (especially if he used to be creative, never got numbers while the fap fic next door blew up, and now just wallows in thingsthatcouldbe.txt), or it could be despair that he won't live up to (false) expectations. And because it's depression, he WANTS to stay where he is because it hurts less to be in the hole than to climb out only to fall back in later. That's how it's a behavioral trap.

The resolution isn't to throw in ropes and ladders (lol infographics) because he won't use them. Those just make it easier to get out which means easier to fall back in.

He needs to be inspired by something that uses whatever skills he has in an unexpected way. Let's say he pretends to be a story writer, and you say that you draw, make him outline and flesh out a short comic (say eight pages, depending on your capacity). Nothing from his "ideas" document, that shit's poison; you put him on task on something out of genre and when he says he doesn't know about that say that you don't care, you're confident it'll be good enough. Require a synopsis (the five act plot arc in one paragraph), outline of the pages, and once you approve that (since you're drawing it) a detailed description of page one (Dialog, description of the panels, whatever you'd need like you were doing commission). If he keeps writing pages, you keep drawing them.

This will not CURE his depression, but it will make proof that he just has to decide to do the work to get something done.

And if he refuses, draw based on my writing instead. :)

I'm In This Post and I Don't Like It. (Not actually your friend, obviously.)
I've got plenty of ideas, but not writing anything. Not even writing down the ideas, just keeping them in my head. The brainstorming is the fun part, while actually writing is almost physically painful. In my head the details are vague. I don't know if it's depression, ADHD, a bit of autism, or none or all of the above, i've just never been able to write at a pace that doesn't make me want to kill myself. He is motivated. Otherwise he wouldn't be making a war chest of ideas. It'd be transactional like you describe if Anon was buying small bits of activity from him with the images but apparently that's not what's happening. Anon is drawing because that was the deal, and he's letting Lazy coast because he knows that Lazy has it in him even though he's stuck in a rut and not actually getting shit off.

That's why I advise creating a new environment of Do A Small Thing Repeatedly (comic arc, outline, comic page, page, page...) instead of piling up "ideas" that never get assembled into something. Lazy needs two things: success and momentum. Small tasks, too small to ruminate over, that get done in one session provide successes and if Lazy can get engaged in a way that one leads to another, there's momentum.

Creativity is a habit. Procrastination is also a habit. The only difference is how much value one *expects* to get from one versus the other. Idea Document gives a false impression of value that keeps building up even though none of that ever materializes. The objective is to reintroduce Lazy to turning tiny amounts of idea into non-tiny amounts of success.
